To create an ASP.NET Core API that proxies requests to another endpoint, you can use the `HttpClient` class to forward incoming requests to the target API. Here's an example of how to do this:

1. Create a new ASP.NET Core Web API project:
```javascript
dotnet new webapi -n MyApiProxy
cd MyApiProxy
```
1. Add the `Microsoft.Extensions.Http` NuGet package:
```java
dotnet add package Microsoft.Extensions.Http
```
1. Open the `Startup.cs` file, and add the following using statements:
```csharp
using System.Net.Http;
using Microsoft.Extensions.DependencyInjection;
```
1. In the `ConfigureServices` method, add the `HttpClient` service:
```csharp
public void ConfigureServices(IServiceCollection services)
{
    services.AddControllers();
    services.AddHttpClient();
}
```
1. Create a new controller called `ProxyController.cs` in the `Controllers` folder and add the following code:
```csharp
using System;
using System.IO;
using System.Net.Http;
using System.Threading.Tasks;
using Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc;

namespace MyApiProxy.Controllers
{
    [ApiController]
    [Route("[controller]")]
    public class ProxyController : ControllerBase
    {
        private readonly HttpClient _httpClient;
        private const string TargetApiBaseUrl = "https://target-api.example.com";

        public ProxyController(HttpClient httpClient)
        {
            _httpClient = httpClient;
        }

        [HttpGet("{*path}")]
        public async Task<IActionResult> Get(string path)
        {
            var requestUri = new Uri(new Uri(TargetApiBaseUrl), path);

            using var httpResponse = await _httpClient.GetAsync(requestUri);
            httpResponse.EnsureSuccessStatusCode();

            var content = await httpResponse.Content.ReadAsStreamAsync();

            return new FileStreamResult(content, httpResponse.Content.Headers.ContentType.ToString());
        }

        // Add additional methods (POST, PUT, DELETE) if needed.
    }
}
```
Make sure to replace `https://target-api.example.com` with the actual URL of the target API.

This example sets up a simple proxy that forwards all incoming GET requests to the specified target API. You can add support for other HTTP methods (POST, PUT, DELETE, etc.) by adding corresponding action methods in the `ProxyController` class.

Keep in mind that this is a simple example and may not cover all use cases. For more complex scenarios or for better performance, consider using a dedicated reverse proxy server like NGINX or a library like YARP (Yet Another Reverse Proxy) for ASP.NET Core.

The provided example only proxies the HTML content of the requested page (in this case, google.com) but does not handle the assets (CSS, JavaScript, images, etc.) that the page may reference. To proxy the assets as well, you'll need to parse the HTML content and rewrite the URLs of the assets to point to your proxy endpoint.

Here's a simple example of how you can achieve this using the `AngleSharp` library to parse and modify the HTML:

1. Add the `AngleSharp` NuGet package:
```java
dotnet add package AngleSharp
```
1. Modify the `ProxyController` class in `Controllers/ProxyController.cs`:
```csharp
using System;
using System.IO;
using System.Net.Http;
using System.Threading.Tasks;
using AngleSharp.Html.Parser;
using Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc;

namespace MyApiProxy.Controllers
{
    [ApiController]
    [Route("[controller]")]
    public class ProxyController : ControllerBase
    {
        private readonly HttpClient _httpClient;
        private const string TargetApiBaseUrl = "https://www.google.com";
        private const string ProxyBaseUrl = "https://your-proxy-api.example.com/proxy";

        public ProxyController(HttpClient httpClient)
        {
            _httpClient = httpClient;
        }

        [HttpGet("{*path}")]
        public async Task<IActionResult> Get(string path)
        {
            var requestUri = new Uri(new Uri(TargetApiBaseUrl), path);

            using var httpResponse = await _httpClient.GetAsync(requestUri);
            httpResponse.EnsureSuccessStatusCode();

            if (httpResponse.Content.Headers.ContentType.MediaType == "text/html")
            {
                var content = await httpResponse.Content.ReadAsStringAsync();
                var parser = new HtmlParser();
                var document = await parser.ParseDocumentAsync(content);

                // Rewrite asset URLs to point to the proxy endpoint
                foreach (var img in document.Images)
                {
                    img.Source = RewriteUrl(img.Source);
                }
                foreach (var link in document.QuerySelectorAll("link[href]"))
                {
                    link.SetAttribute("href", RewriteUrl(link.GetAttribute("href")));
                }
                foreach (var script in document.Scripts)
                {
                    script.Source = RewriteUrl(script.Source);
                }

                content = document.DocumentElement.OuterHtml;
                return Content(content, "text/html");
            }
            else
            {
                var content = await httpResponse.Content.ReadAsStreamAsync();
                return new FileStreamResult(content, httpResponse.Content.Headers.ContentType.ToString());
            }
        }

        private string RewriteUrl(string url)
        {
            if (Uri.IsWellFormedUriString(url, UriKind.Absolute))
            {
                return $"{ProxyBaseUrl}?url={Uri.EscapeDataString(url)}";
            }
            return url;
        }
    }
}
```
1. Make sure to replace `https://your-proxy-api.example.com/proxy` with the actual URL of your proxy API.

This example rewrites URLs of images, CSS, and JavaScript files to point to your proxy endpoint. Keep in mind that this is a simple example, and it might not cover all cases. You might need to adjust the code to handle other types of assets or special cases.

This solution can introduce some overhead in processing and might not be suitable for high-traffic scenarios. In such cases, consider using a dedicated reverse proxy server like NGINX or a library like YARP (Yet Another Reverse Proxy) for ASP.NET Core.

