To configure Serilog to output only the class name without the full namespace, you can create a custom enricher that extracts the class name from the source context. Here's an example of how to do that:

1. First, create a custom enricher class:
```csharp
using Serilog.Core;
using Serilog.Events;
using System;

public class ClassNameEnricher : ILogEventEnricher
{
    public void Enrich(LogEvent logEvent, ILogEventPropertyFactory propertyFactory)
    {
        if (logEvent.Properties.TryGetValue("SourceContext", out LogEventPropertyValue sourceContextValue))
        {
            if (sourceContextValue is ScalarValue scalarValue && scalarValue.Value is string sourceContext)
            {
                string className = GetClassNameFromSourceContext(sourceContext);
                logEvent.AddOrUpdateProperty(propertyFactory.CreateProperty("ClassName", className));
            }
        }
    }

    private string GetClassNameFromSourceContext(string sourceContext)
    {
        string[] parts = sourceContext.Split('.');
        return parts.Length > 0 ? parts[^1] : sourceContext;
    }
}
```
This custom enricher class checks if the `SourceContext` property exists in the log event. If it does, it extracts the class name from the source context, and adds a new property `ClassName` to the log event.

1. Configure Serilog to use the custom enricher and output the class name in the log messages:
```csharp
using Serilog;
using Serilog.Formatting.Json;

public class Program
{
    public static void Main()
    {
        Log.Logger = new LoggerConfiguration()
            .Enrich.With<ClassNameEnricher>()
            .WriteTo.Console(new JsonFormatter())
            .CreateLogger();

        Log.Information("This is an information message.");
    }
}
```
In this example, Serilog is configured to use the custom `ClassNameEnricher`. The log output is formatted as JSON, but you can change the output format to your preference.

Now, when you log messages, the class name will be included in the `ClassName` property without the full namespace. Note that this solution assumes you are using the `SourceContext` property to store the class information. If your setup is different, you may need to adjust the code accordingly.

