To access a user's microphone from their browser, you can use the Web Audio API and the MediaDevices.getUserMedia() method. This is supported by modern browsers such as Chrome, Firefox, Safari, and Edge.

Here's a simple example to access the user's microphone and stream the audio input:

1. Create an HTML file with a button to request microphone access:
```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Microphone Access</title>
</head>
<body>
    <button id="start">Start Microphone</button>
    <script src="script.js"></script>
</body>
</html>
```
1. Create a JavaScript file (script.js) to handle the microphone access:
```javascript
document.getElementById('start').addEventListener('click', async () => {
    try {
        const stream = await navigator.mediaDevices.getUserMedia({ audio: true });
        const audioContext = new AudioContext();
        const source = audioContext.createMediaStreamSource(stream);
        const gainNode = audioContext.createGain();
        const destination = audioContext.destination;

        // Connect the audio nodes
        source.connect(gainNode);
        gainNode.connect(destination);

        // You can adjust the gain value to control the volume
        gainNode.gain.value = 1.0;
    } catch (error) {
        console.error('Error accessing microphone:', error);
    }
});
```
In this example, the audio input from the microphone is simply connected to the audio output, so you'll hear the audio through the speakers or headphones. You can further process the audio stream according to your needs.

Please note that getUserMedia() requires the site to be served over HTTPS, or accessed via localhost during development.

For more advanced use cases, you can check out the official Web Audio API documentation: <https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/Web_Audio_API>

To build a simple command-line tool using JavaScript that converts an image (PNG or JPEG) to an SVG format, you can use the `potrace` library. Here's how you can create the script:

1. First, make sure you have Node.js installed on your computer. If you don't have it, download and install it from <https://nodejs.org/en/download/>.
2. Create a new folder for your project and navigate to it in the command line or terminal.
3. Run `npm init` and follow the prompts to create a `package.json` file for your project.
4. Install the `potrace` library by running `npm install potrace`.
5. Create a new file in your project folder called `convertImageToSVG.js` and add the following code:
```javascript
const fs = require('fs');
const potrace = require('potrace');
const {promisify} = require('util');

const trace = promisify(potrace.trace);

if (process.argv.length < 4) {
  console.log('Usage: node convertImageToSVG.js input.png output.svg');
  process.exit(1);
}

const inputFilePath = process.argv[2];
const outputFilePath = process.argv[3];

fs.readFile(inputFilePath, async (err, imageData) => {
  if (err) {
    console.error('Error reading input file:', err);
    process.exit(1);
  }

  try {
    const svg = await trace(imageData);
    fs.writeFileSync(outputFilePath, svg);
    console.log(`SVG saved to ${outputFilePath}`);
  } catch (error) {
    console.error('Error converting image to SVG:', error);
    process.exit(1);
  }
});
```
1. To use the script, run the following command in your terminal:
```lua
node convertImageToSVG.js input.png output.svg
```
Replace `input.png` with the path to your input image (PNG or JPEG), and `output.svg` with the path where you want to save the SVG file.

Please note that this script uses a simple tracing algorithm and might not produce the best results for complex images. For more advanced image-to-vector conversions, you might want to consider using an online service or dedicated software like Adobe Illustrator.

